50|$|According to {{communist}} ideologists, the Soviet {{political system}} {{was a true}} democracy, where workers' councils ("soviets") represented {{the will of the}} working class. In particular, the Soviet Constitution of 1936 guaranteed <b>direct</b> universal <b>suffrage</b> with the secret ballot. Practice, however, departed from principle. For example, all candidates had been selected by Communist Party organizations before the June 1987 elections.|$|R
50|$|It {{comprises}} 120 members called honorable deputies (H.D.), who {{are elected}} to four-year terms, by <b>direct</b> universal <b>suffrage,</b> from 60 two-member electoral districts. Deputies must: be aged at least 21; not be disqualified from voting; have finished secondary school or its equivalent; and {{have lived in}} the corresponding electoral district {{for at least two years}} prior to the election.|$|R
